##How can I volunteer if I'M NOT IN WUHAN

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Huazhong University of Science and Technology 2017 undergraduate student

On January 16, Summer, a senior at Wuhan Media College, boarded a flight from Wuhan. According to the original plan, after attending the event in Xiamen, he will return to Baekdu Mountain and shut down the Internet to write.

No one wears a mask at Wuhan Tianhe Airport. He did not know at that time, the new coronavirus has quietly spread in Wuhan. He did not expect that the city would be closed in a week's time, and that he would not be able to return to the city, which contained many of his memories and feelings, any time soon.

The News of the closure came suddenly, and before Summer could change her flight ticket, the access to Han was cut off. He said he would have stayed in Wuhan if he had known the epidemic would be so severe.

From the day the city was shut down, Summer became an online volunteer. For more than a month, he was on the other side of the screen, helping more than 30 patients, connecting donations to more than 14 hospitals that were asking for help from the community, and still constantly feeling small and powerless. He is eager to return to Wuhan to do more and help more people.

Here's Summer's dictation

It came in at 0:46

At 00:46 on January 27, while I was busy trying to figure out how to deliver a donation to a designated hospital, Xiu sent a message asking me: could you please contact the volunteer driver to take her father to the hospital? That was the first time she asked me for help.

SU-SU is a classmate of mine. She knows I'm volunteering. I went to school in Wuhan and worked there one after another for a long time. I always claimed to be a new Wuhan native. I happened to study journalism and had some social resources. I wanted to use my own resources to help Wuhan. Since volunteering, I've been working from 8:30 am to 2:30 am.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After volunteering, Summer works until the wee hours of the morning.

XIUXIU's father has been quarantined at home since January 20, when he developed fever, cough and other symptoms. In the early hours of the morning of the 27th, his condition worsened and his temperature rose to 38.5 degrees. He was diagnosed by the community health service as a highly probable patient and needed to be taken to the hospital immediately. Xiu Xiu called 120, but there is no empty car, community vehicles can not send patients, designated hospitals can not get through the phone, the situation is very urgent.

I told her to take her time and suggested she call 110 and contact the right person. Meanwhile, I spread the message among my friends and hospitals, and contacted the epidemic command. At 1:37 in the morning, Xiu Xiu hair informed me that the car had been contacted and was on its way.

I thought I would be safe at the hospital, but at 6 p.m. on Jan. 28, I received another call from Xiu: After her father was sent to Wugang No. 2 Hospital, medical staff could not examine and treat him further because the hospital was not fully equipped. Xiu Xiu feared that her father's condition would worsen and hoped to be transferred to a hospital with better medical facilities.

I forwarded her requests to reporters and helped spread the word among friends and my own media. But I also know that hospitals have long been overloaded. Besides, it's GonNa be hard to get out of here once you're in the hospital. So I told xiu-xiu to prepare herself.

Luckily, on the afternoon of the 29th, Xiu told me the good news: My father was already in line for a nucleic acid test. She was worried about his cross-infection in the hospital and wanted him to be put under house arrest for a while before he was tested, and the doctor agreed. Later, she got in touch with the car to take her father home. It seemed like everything was going so well.

At 8 p.m. , Xiu sent me another message: She had been in front of the hospital for so long that she could see her father, who was a door away, but he didn't come out. At that time, part of the area has begun to close down the community, time is very tight. I tried to get the number of my contact at the hospital, but it didn't arrive. We contacted the outbreak command center and the community, and we didn't get a definitive answer. I couldn't get to the scene. I felt overwhelmed.

SU-SU's father didn't get out of the hospital. Later, Xiu Xiu's father became seriously ill. She asked me how I could get the IMMUNOGLOBULIN, and I helped her find a way according to her request.

Xiu Xiu later found the IMMUNOGLOBULIN, after a few days, she did not ask me for help, I did not ask. During the outbreak, no news was good news. Generally speaking, in the hospital, with the doctor and medicine, there is no problem. These days, although the process of contacting each channel is very tortuous, but in the end most of the problems still can be solved.

15-man support group

Unexpectedly, when I received Xiu Xiu's request for help again, I received bad news one after another about her mother's illness and her father's death.

On February 5, Xiu asked me to help her contact a car to take her to a designated hospital for a CT scan. On the 7th, Xiu Xiu's father went into shock and was transferred to the Wuhan Union Hospital, where he died on the 8th morning.

I was shocked and I blamed myself. I was the first person at my school to know about Xiu Xiu's father's illness. Xiu-xiu chose me first to ask for help, which means she trusts me, and I think I may have betrayed her trust.

I thought, if I had been there on January 29th, when sho-su's father couldn't be released, would it have made a difference? My major is related to media, my previous work experience is also related to journalists and public relations, and I have some experience in dealing with people on the spot. Xiu was also scared that night, and if she had a calm person to deal with it on the spot, things might have turned out better, at least more than I could have done online.

Since then, Xiu's classmates have formed a 15-person support group, seven of whom are the main force, and other volunteers guerrilla help. There was a clear division of Labor within the team: I was in charge of contacting Xiu, asking about Xiu's mother, getting inside information about the bed, and also communicating with the media about the show. Other volunteers are in charge of liaising with concerned citizens, managing accounts and procuring medicines; collecting and Verifying Hospital Information and contacting beds; and calming down the show.

Xiuxiu's mother was finally admitted to Hankou Hospital in the early hours of October 10, but the condition was serious and the doctor issued a critical notice that day. Two days ago, Xiu Xiu and her brother also had a CT scan. They both had suspected lung infections. Xiu-xiu's symptoms were more severe and she was later diagnosed.

My father had died, my mother was very ill, I had been diagnosed myself, and Xiu was not in a good state for a few days. Well, we don't have to ask, because there's nothing anyone can do about it. So at the beginning, everyone dare not communicate with Xiu Xiu, for fear of touching her tears.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"Xiu Xiu wants to be a big Sun, " she wrote on her Weibo Account, which was nicknamed "Xiu Xiu wants to be a big Sun. " She "has been trying to be a lucky sun all along. ".

Over the past several days, I have helped more than 30 patients, and Xiu Xiu is the sunniest and strongest person I have ever met. By the time other people came to me for help, I had already sent out a lot of negative friend groups or posts. But when Xiu first asked for help, she said nothing, and she didn't blame anyone. She says she is very understanding and has been working with the community on the work and processes. She didn't even ask for help on social media until she reached out to me, and she didn't have to bother anyone until my dad got worse. Xiu Xiu's screen name is "Xiu Xiu to do big Sun" , she is very cheerful in the reality, is also very willing to help others.

Want to do more

Volunteer help isn't always effective. It's not that volunteers don't do something, it's that after a lot of hard work, the results don't look good. It's like we're trying to help a patient, we've tried every avenue we have, but no one can save the patient, and the doctors and the volunteers are running around, and it's the same state of mind. Powerlessness is always with us, but no one gives up easily.

The feeling of powerlessness is most intense in early February. That few days, the material just tightened, "should receive receives receives receives receives" the policy also to have not come out. At that time, medical materials had already been uniformly controlled and produced by the relevant departments. As private volunteers, we could not buy them. Even if the materials had already been paid for, the manufacturers would not deliver them, so there's no way we can supply the front. On the other hand, patients have been asking for beds, but at that time the beds are relatively tight, we try to rescue them, but the actual number of rescue is not very many.

On February 5, I posted a friend's circle: "channels are getting tighter. How can we do more? "

Those few days were a dark period for the civilian volunteers. Because the civilian volunteers mainly do material donations and patient relief, at that time, these two sections can not function properly, but everyone never stopped. Some volunteers are looking for a new factory, others for a refund, but after a few days of "struggle" , we found that more and more cheaters, it is really difficult to find reliable medical supplies. Our volunteers are lucky, because we do a lot of sections, we can also check information, but also to the official media to provide news leads.

We feel powerless whether we can save them or not. In the face of great disaster, the individual is extremely small. I myself had been able to get supplies to a dozen hospitals, but after only a day, they were running low again. Volunteers may be able to get a bed for a few patients who need help, but they can't do it with the thousands of people who need help. I can only say that "grief can pull out the bitter, mercy and joy" , although small, but can save a is a.

We're also expanding into volunteering in the area of household goods donations, such as disposable bowls and chopsticks, instant noodles and toilet paper at the shelter hospital. Now, fewer patients come to us for help than before, and since yesterday (February 26) , we have not received any more requests for bed help. For patients, convalescent plasma is what they need most right now. Our team has a volunteer who checks and collates the information of the patients who ask for help every day, but this is a very complicated matter, so there is no successful case yet.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Summer still has 17,912 unread messages left on her wechat account after 8 p.m. on Feb. 22, and can not rest until he has read and processed all of them. Such intensive work has become the norm since I started volunteering.

To be honest, this period of time to do volunteers than I have before the intensity of study and work. I receive more than 30,000 messages on wechat every day, and I won't sleep until I've dealt with that day's events. The last day, I remember very clearly, I had three patients asking for help at 10 pm, and I didn't rest until 3:40 am that day. My phone's memory is 128 gigabytes, and now wechat alone accounts for half of it. My phone even went on strike for a day on February 5th.

Volunteer is not like study, tired can rest; also not like I prefer to do before the freelancing, do not want to do not do. Once you start doing it, you have to keep doing it, no matter what happens. Because people are counting on you to take responsibility for their lives.

On January 16, I left Wuhan on a business trip to Xiamen, and then wanted to go back to Wuhan to volunteer on the front line, but I couldn't get in any way. Now that I can do so much online, I can do so much more offline. If I had known it would come to this, I would never have left Wuhan.

(instructors: Huazhong University of Science and Technology, Zhou Tingting; _ thepaper.cn, Zhang Xiaolian)
